data.content:
Use EF Core 7+'s **bulk operations** — `ExecuteUpdateAsync` and `ExecuteDeleteAsync`. They translate directly to SQL, bypassing the change tracker entirely:

```csharp
// Operation 1: Bulk update — generates a single UPDATE statement
var cutoffDate = DateTime.UtcNow.AddMonths(-6);
await _db.Products
    .Where(p => p.LastSoldDate < cutoffDate)
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s => s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

// Operation 2: Bulk delete — generates a single DELETE statement
var logCutoff = DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1);
await _db.AuditLogs
    .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < logCutoff)
    .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

**Key differences:**
- **No entity loading** — executes directly as SQL (`UPDATE ... SET ... WHERE ...`)
- **No change tracker** — much lower memory; no `SaveChangesAsync()` needed
- **Single roundtrip** — one statement instead of thousands of individual updates
- **Caveat** — bypasses EF interceptors, navigation fixup, and concurrency tokens. Any tracked entities of those types will be stale after the call.

If you need concurrency safety or the tables are very large (millions of deletes can cause lock escalation), batch with a loop:

```csharp
int batchSize = 10_000;
int affected;
do
{
    affected = await _db.AuditLogs
        .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < logCutoff)
        .Take(batchSize)
        .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
} while (affected == batchSize);
```
